-- allium: 3
-- specs/dflash/cb_eval_residual_capture.allium
--
-- Scope: the implementation-level contract for capturing per-layer
-- residual streams from the target during a llama_decode call, for
-- consumption by the DFlash drafter's combine_features + inject_kv
-- path. The abstract behaviour ("extract features at a configured
-- layer subset") is owned by specs/dflash/dflash.allium's
-- ExtractFeatures contract. THIS spec narrows the implementation
-- mechanism, because the choice of mechanism is load-bearing on
-- target-forward determinism and the obvious choice (scheduler
-- eval-callback) violates it.
--
-- Why this spec exists: P0.A.3 falsification matrix (2026-05-20)
-- confirmed that the DFlash CLI on production/2026-q2-next emits
-- garbled output ("user user wants wants quick quick") while
-- spec-none and `--spec-type ngram-simple` on the same prompt /
-- seed / batch shape produce clean, byte-identical-to-baseline
-- output. The single architectural difference DFlash carries over
-- ngram-simple is the cb_eval hook installed by
-- llama_set_dflash_extract_layers. The hook returns `true` on
-- `ask=true` for the configured `l_out-<il>` source-layer nodes
-- and the scheduler responds by splitting each per-backend split
-- into N small subgraphs (one per gap between watched nodes),
-- inserting ggml_backend_synchronize between each, then issuing N
-- separate ggml_backend_graph_compute_async calls. Each
-- sub-invocation lets the CUDA backend re-plan fusion / re-issue
-- cudaGraph capture / re-pick cuBLAS algos on a *different*
-- contiguous-node range than the fast path would. The argmax flip
-- cascades through 65 transformer layers and breaks DFlash verify.
--
-- The fix is to mirror what MTP already does (and what production
-- relies on for byte-identity): emit dedicated tap nodes inside
-- the graph builder, mark them with ggml_set_output, leave the
-- scheduler on its fast path (no eval-callback). Production MTP
-- ships with `h_pre_norm` and `result_output` tap nodes
-- (build_qwen35.cpp:96-99,205-208) and is byte-identical to
-- spec-none. Residual capture must use the same mechanism.
--
-- Includes:
--   - External entities for the runtime objects involved (the
--     graph, the scheduler, the per-split sub-graphs, the
--     extract configuration, the tap nodes, the residual buffers
--     keyed by layer + seq_id).
--   - Enumerations for the two candidate mechanisms
--     (scheduler_callback, graph_tap_node) and the residual
--     tensor dtype that may legitimately reach the host buffer.
--   - Contracts for ResidualExtract (the public surface),
--     SchedulerFastPath (the property the implementation must
--     not violate), and GraphTapEmission (the required mechanism
--     in build_qwen35* graph builders).
--   - System-wide invariants binding the observational
--     equivalence of decode-with-extract vs decode-without-extract
--     and naming the forbidden mechanism explicitly.
--   - Open questions for the design points the
--     replacement-of-cb_eval refactor must commit to.
--
-- Excludes:
--   - The downstream consumption of the captured residuals
--     (combine_features GEMM, inject_kv_fused, drafter_forward).
--     Owned by specs/dflash/dflash.allium contracts ProjectAndFuse
--     and DraftBlockEmit.
--   - The cb_eval callback's *type-handling* logic (F16 vs F32
--     rows, seq_id demux). That logic is correct; the mechanism
--     itself is wrong. Removing the cb_eval hook removes the
--     bug.
--   - The MTP fused draft graph (mtp_fused_draft.allium). MTP
--     uses tap nodes already and is not affected. This spec
--     converges DFlash onto the same architectural footing.
--   - The DFlash drafter's internal layers. Untouched.
--   - The 4D per-stream KV layout (n_stream_layer.allium). The
--     post-fold submodule already runs n_stream=2 in production;
--     P0.A.3's bug is independent of n_stream.

-- ============================================================
-- External entities — runtime objects we constrain
-- ============================================================

-- One ggml backend scheduler instance owned by a llama_context.
-- The scheduler dispatches compute on the per-backend "splits"
-- of the inference cgraph and invokes the per-tensor eval
-- callback at fixed points if one is installed. Lives at
-- ggml-backend.cpp:1173-1174 (callback_eval field) and is wired
-- via ggml_backend_sched_set_eval_callback at line 2669.
external entity SchedulerInstance {
    has_eval_callback: Boolean
}

-- One "split" of the cgraph for a single backend. The scheduler
-- builds these in ggml_backend_sched_compute_splits and dispatches
-- each via ggml_backend_sched_eval at ggml-backend.cpp:2126. The
-- fast path (no callback) executes the whole split in ONE
-- ggml_backend_graph_compute_async call. The slow path (callback
-- installed) iterates node-by-node and breaks into sub-graphs at
-- every node where callback_eval returns true on ask=true.
external entity GraphSplit {
    n_nodes: Integer
    n_subgraph_invocations: Integer
}

-- The runtime configuration that arms (or disarms) residual
-- capture for the current llama_context. Mirrors
-- llama_cparams.dflash_extract_count + dflash_extract_layers[80]
-- (src/llama-cparams.h, set via llama_set_dflash_extract_layers
-- at src/llama.cpp:10051-10082).
external entity ExtractConfig {
    layer_count: Integer            -- 0 disables; >0 selects layers
    layer_ids: List<Integer>        -- which il indices to capture
    enabled: Boolean                -- derived: layer_count > 0
}

-- One ggml tensor node in the cgraph that the graph builder
-- emits specifically as a "tap" for residual extraction. It
-- carries the value of a per-layer residual stream (`l_out-<il>`
-- for the qwen35 family) but is NOT consumed by any downstream
-- compute node — it exists only so its data is reachable from
-- host code after llama_decode returns. Marked with
-- ggml_set_output so the allocator places it in the output
-- buffer pool. Compare build_qwen35.cpp:96-99
-- (`embd_copy = ggml_dup(...); cb(..., "h_pre_norm", -1);
-- ggml_set_output(embd_copy)`).
external entity TapNode {
    layer_index: Integer
    name: String                    -- e.g. "l_out_tap-<il>"
    is_output: Boolean              -- ggml_set_output was called
    feeds_compute_node: Boolean     -- MUST be false for tap nodes
}

-- The host-side residual buffer keyed by (layer_slot, seq_id).
-- Populated by the post-decode read path (graph_tap_node
-- mechanism: ggml_backend_tensor_get on the named TapNode;
-- legacy scheduler_callback mechanism: rows appended by the
-- cb_eval callback during graph execution). Owned by
-- llama_decoder.dflash_extract_buf[layer_slot][seq_id] (see
-- include/llama-decoder.h:164-174).
external entity ResidualBuffer {
    layer_slot: Integer
    seq_id: Integer
    n_rows: Integer
    row_dim: Integer
    dtype: ResidualDtype
}

-- A specific llama_decode call. The unit at which the
-- observational-equivalence property is asserted: target forward
-- output must be the same with or without extract armed,
-- pointwise on every produced logit row.
external entity DecodeCall {
    n_tokens: Integer
    extract_armed: Boolean
    out_logits_hash: String         -- abstract digest of post-llama_decode logits
    out_argmax: List<Integer>       -- argmax token per output row
}

-- ============================================================
-- Enumerations
-- ============================================================

-- The two candidate implementation mechanisms for moving
-- residual-stream rows from device to host. Only `graph_tap_node`
-- is permitted by this spec; `scheduler_callback` is named so
-- that ForbiddenMechanism can refer to it.
enum CaptureMechanism {
    scheduler_callback              -- FORBIDDEN: cb_eval, perturbs forward
    graph_tap_node                  -- REQUIRED: ggml_dup + ggml_set_output
}

-- The dtype the tap node may carry. F32 is the canonical case
-- (single-token decode collapses to a 1D residual in build_qwen35
-- as F32). F16 is the multi-token prefill / verify case (the
-- residual stream is F16 when n_tokens > 1). Both are converted
-- to F32 on the host side at read time.
enum ResidualDtype { f32 | f16 }

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- The maximum number of extract layers the implementation
    -- must support. Mirrors LLAMA_DFLASH_MAX_EXTRACT_LAYERS in
    -- src/llama-cparams.h (and the cap enforced in
    -- llama_set_dflash_extract_layers at src/llama.cpp:10053).
    -- The DFlash drafter for Qwen3.6-27B uses 5 layers
    -- (1, 16, 31, 46, 61); the cap is 80.
    max_extract_layers: Integer = 80

    -- The maximum sequences-per-decode the implementation must
    -- support, used for per-seq demux of the residual rows.
    -- Mirrors cparams.n_seq_max; production runs with 2 today.
    max_seq_per_decode: Integer = 8
}

-- ============================================================
-- Contracts
-- ============================================================

-- The public surface for residual capture. Whatever mechanism
-- the implementation picks, the BEHAVIOUR observed by DFlash
-- drafter code is: "after llama_decode returns, the host buffer
-- for layer L and seq_id S contains the residual rows produced
-- during that decode call". This contract is mechanism-agnostic
-- on its own; the mechanism is constrained by
-- SchedulerFastPath + ForbiddenMechanism below.
--
-- Tied to source:
--   - public C API:
--       include/llama.h llama_set_dflash_extract_layers
--       include/llama.h llama_get_dflash_extract_data_seq
--   - implementation today:
--       src/llama.cpp:9961-10049  llama_dflash_extract_cb_eval (TO BE REMOVED)
--       src/llama.cpp:10051-10082 llama_set_dflash_extract_layers
--       src/llama.cpp:10088-...   llama_get_dflash_extract_data_seq
--   - consumer:
--       src/llama-dflash.cpp:552-... stage_target_hiddens
contract ResidualExtract {
    invoke: (target: TargetModel, cfg: ExtractConfig, decode: DecodeCall) -> List<ResidualBuffer>

    @invariant LayerSlotEqualsConfigLayerIndex
        -- The ResidualBuffer at layer_slot k carries the residual
        -- for ExtractConfig.layer_ids[k]. The drafter is trained
        -- against a SPECIFIC tuple of target layer indices (see
        -- ExtractFeatures.UniformSampleSpacing in dflash.allium);
        -- swapping slots is silent corruption.

    @invariant RowsAlignWithDecodeOutputs
        -- For every (layer_slot, seq_id) ResidualBuffer, n_rows
        -- equals the number of rows that contributed to the
        -- decode's output for that seq_id. For single-token
        -- decode this is 1; for multi-token verify of a draft
        -- block of size B the slot's verify-batch contributes B
        -- rows.

    @invariant SeqIdDemuxByUbatchRowSeq
        -- Rows of a multi-seq ubatch are demuxed to the
        -- per-seq_id ResidualBuffer using the dispatch-time row→seq_id
        -- map (llama_decoder.dflash_ubatch_row_seq, populated by
        -- the ubatch builder; see include/llama-decoder.h:164). The
        -- spec does not constrain the demux site (callback or
        -- post-decode loop) — only that rows land in the buffer
        -- whose seq_id matches their batch row.

    @invariant ConfigChangeBetweenDecodesIsAllowed
        -- llama_set_dflash_extract_layers may be called between
        -- llama_decode invocations. Once a decode is in flight,
        -- the configuration may not change. The implementation
        -- must reject config changes that would race a live
        -- decode (or document that this is undefined).

    @invariant DisarmReleasesScheduler
        -- When ExtractConfig.layer_count = 0, the implementation
        -- must restore the scheduler to its fast path: no
        -- callback_eval installed, one ggml_backend_graph_compute_async
        -- per split. Specifically, llama_set_dflash_extract_layers(0)
        -- must clear cparams.cb_eval IFF the cb_eval pointer is
        -- the dflash-installed one (don't stomp third-party
        -- callbacks unrelated to dflash).
}

-- The property the implementation must not violate: the
-- scheduler stays on its fast path during a llama_decode call.
-- This is the mirror image of the forbidden mechanism — phrasing
-- it positively lets propagate generate a binding test that
-- inspects scheduler state directly rather than only the
-- observable output.
--
-- Tied to source:
--   - the slow path: ggml-backend.cpp:2136-2173 (the
--     callback-armed branch of ggml_backend_sched_eval)
--   - the fast path: ggml-backend.cpp:2127-2135 (the single
--     ggml_backend_graph_compute_async call for the whole split)
contract SchedulerFastPath {
    invoke: (sched: SchedulerInstance, split: GraphSplit) -> GraphSplit

    @invariant OneSubgraphPerSplit
        -- For every GraphSplit dispatched during a DecodeCall
        -- whose ExtractConfig.enabled is true OR false,
        -- split.n_subgraph_invocations = 1. The scheduler must
        -- invoke ggml_backend_graph_compute_async exactly once
        -- per split; the callback-armed slow path at
        -- ggml-backend.cpp:2136-2173 must not run.

    @invariant NoEvalCallbackInstalled
        -- During llama_decode, sched.has_eval_callback = false.
        -- This is the spec-level binding of "no cb_eval, ever,
        -- during inference". The scheduler may legitimately
        -- carry a callback for other purposes (graph diffing,
        -- ggml_backend_compare_graph_backend) but those are not
        -- on the inference path.

    @guidance
        -- The forbidden combination is: the scheduler has an
        -- eval callback that returns true on `ask=true` for ANY
        -- node in the inference graph. That's what triggers the
        -- node-by-node iteration in ggml_backend_sched_eval and
        -- breaks fusion. A callback that always returns false on
        -- ask=true is technically allowed by ggml-backend.cpp
        -- (the per-node ask loop still walks node-by-node even
        -- though no node is "needed"), but the spec's
        -- OneSubgraphPerSplit forbids that walk too: every extra
        -- per-node check is a perturbation surface.
}

-- The required mechanism for getting residual data out of the
-- graph. The graph builder emits dedicated tap nodes that
-- duplicate the `l_out-<il>` residual to a buffer owned by the
-- output pool. The MTP path in the same builder already uses
-- this mechanism for `h_pre_norm` and `result_output`; this
-- contract narrows DFlash residual capture to the same
-- mechanism.
--
-- Tied to source:
--   - the MTP reference pattern:
--       src/graphs/build_qwen35.cpp:96-99 (build_qwen35moe)
--       src/graphs/build_qwen35.cpp:205-208 (build_qwen35)
--   - the residual nodes to be tapped:
--       src/graphs/build_qwen35.cpp:75 (cb(cur, "l_out", il) in moe)
--       src/graphs/build_qwen35.cpp:193 (cb(cur, "l_out", il) in dense)
--   - the existing extract-config the new tap emission consumes:
--       src/llama-cparams.h dflash_extract_layers[80]
contract GraphTapEmission {
    invoke: (target: TargetModel, cfg: ExtractConfig) -> List<TapNode>

    @invariant OneTapPerConfiguredLayer
        -- For every il in cfg.layer_ids, the graph builder emits
        -- exactly one TapNode whose layer_index = il. No tap
        -- nodes are emitted for layers not in cfg.layer_ids.
        -- When cfg.enabled is false, no tap nodes are emitted.

    @invariant TapNameMatchesLayerIndex
        -- TapNode.name follows a stable convention. The current
        -- choice is "l_out_tap-<il>". The name is used only for
        -- post-decode lookup via ggml_get_tensor + may also be
        -- used in diag prints. Cross-referencing the existing
        -- "h_pre_norm" / "result_output" pattern in
        -- build_qwen35.cpp:97,103 confirms the name-as-handle
        -- convention is load-bearing for the MTP path too.

    @invariant TapIsLeafInGraph
        -- TapNode.feeds_compute_node = false. The tap is a
        -- terminal in the cgraph: ggml_build_forward_expand
        -- enrols it as a graph output, no downstream op consumes
        -- it. This is what keeps the tap from forming a fusion
        -- partner with the next layer's first compute node. The
        -- MTP `h_pre_norm` example at build_qwen35.cpp:96-99
        -- is a leaf in exactly this sense.

    @invariant TapIsCheapDuplicate
        -- The tap node is a single ggml_dup of the residual
        -- (`l_out-<il>`). It performs one tensor copy of the
        -- residual into the output buffer. No quantisation, no
        -- norm, no projection — those happen on the host side
        -- (or in the drafter's combine_features) where the
        -- forward path is no longer running.

    @invariant TapPlacementAfterCvecApply
        -- Source tap point is the residual AFTER lctx.cvec.apply_to
        -- (build_qwen35.cpp:74 and :192 in moe/dense), which is
        -- the same point cb names "l_out-<il>". Placing the tap
        -- before cvec.apply_to would change which residual
        -- stream the drafter sees and is a different feature
        -- definition.
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants — system-wide
-- ============================================================

-- The load-bearing observational property. For a fixed
-- (target, prompt, seed, cparams\\{extract}) tuple, the post-decode
-- logits — and therefore the argmax token stream — must be the
-- same whether ExtractConfig.enabled is true or false. This is
-- the property whose VIOLATION is the P0.A.3 bug today: the
-- spec-none baseline ("\\n\\n<think>\\nHere's a thinking
-- process...") differs from the cb_eval-armed DFlash output
-- ("user user wants wants...") with everything else fixed.
invariant ResidualExtractObservationallyEquivalent {
    for da in DecodeCalls:
        for db in DecodeCalls:
            (da.n_tokens = db.n_tokens
             and da.extract_armed = false
             and db.extract_armed = true)
            implies da.out_argmax = db.out_argmax
}

-- The forbidden mechanism, stated as an invariant on the
-- system-wide implementation. Every captured ResidualBuffer
-- must trace its origin to a TapNode in the cgraph, not to a
-- scheduler callback. Property-test generation off this
-- invariant should emit a test that inspects sched.has_eval_callback
-- inside a wrapped llama_decode call.
invariant CaptureMechanismIsTapNode {
    for buf in ResidualBuffers:
        ProvenanceOf(buf) = graph_tap_node
}

-- The two invariants above compose: they REQUIRE
-- observational equivalence AND name the only implementation
-- mechanism that achieves it. Together they let propagate
-- generate a test that (a) compares argmax sequences across
-- extract on/off, (b) asserts no scheduler callback is
-- installed during the extract-on decode. (a) without (b)
-- catches the bug but not the mechanism; (b) without (a) lets
-- a different perturbation slip through.

-- ============================================================
-- Open questions
-- ============================================================

-- OQ-CB-EVAL-DEPRECATION
-- The cb_eval surface is still public on llama_context_params
-- (include/llama.h:481-482). Third-party consumers may install
-- their own callbacks for unrelated reasons. The spec's
-- NoEvalCallbackInstalled invariant binds only on the DFlash
-- extract path; it does not deprecate the field. Should the
-- field be deprecated entirely now that DFlash no longer uses
-- it, or left as a public hatch with a documented "do not use
-- during inference" warning? Decide before P0.A.3 closure
-- ships.

-- OQ-LEGACY-INTEGRATION-TESTS
-- libllama has multi-slot DFlash test harnesses (tests/
-- test-dflash-np-multislot, test-dflash-closure) that
-- currently pass byte-identity using the cb_eval mechanism.
-- They MUST also pass with the new tap-node mechanism — but
-- since the tap-node mechanism produces byte-identical
-- target-forward output by construction (spec-none baseline
-- = tap-armed output), and the per-row content of the
-- residual buffers is unchanged (same tensor, same elements,
-- same demux), the libllama tests should continue to pass
-- without modification. Confirm under test-first design.

-- OQ-TAP-NODE-ALLOCATOR-COST
-- ggml_set_output places the tap in the output buffer pool.
-- For 5 source layers x [D_emb x n_tokens] residuals at F32,
-- this is 5 * 5120 * 1 * 4 = 100 KB per single-token decode
-- and 5 * 5120 * 16 * 4 = 1.6 MB per 16-token verify. The
-- allocator already handles `result_output` which is
-- vocab_size * n_tokens * 4 = 248320 * 16 * 4 ≈ 15 MB, so
-- the tap nodes are an order of magnitude smaller. Confirm
-- in N1 that the output buffer pool sizing accommodates
-- without recompute.

-- OQ-MULTI-TOKEN-DTYPE
-- The current cb_eval code branches on t->type to handle F32
-- vs F16 (src/llama.cpp:10011-10047). With tap nodes, the
-- builder controls the dtype of the duplicated tensor. The
-- simplest choice is to ggml_dup the residual at its native
-- dtype (F16 for multi-token, F32 for single-token), then
-- convert F16→F32 on the host side post-decode using the
-- existing ggml_fp16_to_fp32_row helper. Alternative: insert
-- a ggml_cast to F32 in the graph so the tap is uniformly
-- F32. Decide based on a single allium check + test pass.

-- @guidance
--     This spec is INTENTIONALLY narrow on mechanism. The
--     dflash.allium ExtractFeatures contract is abstract on
--     mechanism — it says "extract residuals at the configured
--     layers, deterministically". This refinement says "and
--     don't do it with a scheduler eval-callback because that
--     specific mechanism perturbs the forward path on our
--     CUDA backend". A different backend (CPU, Metal) might
--     not exhibit the perturbation. The spec is still correct
--     on those backends; the forbidden-mechanism invariant
--     defaults to redundant rather than wrong. The
--     justification for the narrowness is empirical — see
--     PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md P0.A.3 falsification matrix.
